    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and im kinda confused. even though i'm paying the same amount every month, the actual principal balance barely seems to go down in the first few years. can u explain how the interest calculation actually works on a declining balance?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Your payment is split between interest and principal, and in the early years of a student loan, a larger portion goes toward interest because it is calculated on your *current* outstanding balance. As you make your payments, the principal balance decreases, which means less interest accrues in subsequent months, causing more of each fixed payment to eventually go toward reducing the principal itself. This structural behavior explains why the principal balance appears to stay stubbornly high initially before dropping off faster later in the loan term.",
