    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, but it feels almost like the interest is eating up my payments before they even hit the principal. is there any way to calculate exactly how much of my monthly payment is being lost to interest vs what's actually paying down the loan, so i can see that breakdown better?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, your amortization schedule or most loan servicer apps already display a detailed breakdown for every single month, usually labeled as \"Payment,\" \"Interest,\" and \"Principal.\" By looking at the \"Interest\" column, you can see exactly how much is lost to interest that month, while the difference between your total payment and that interest amount is what reduces your principal balance. If this column seems overwhelming, many calculators allow you to \"extrapolate\" or use the \"Rule of 78s\" for old loans to project total interest costs, but viewing your specific monthly line item is the most direct way to see the split.",
      "source": "target",
