    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "it just feels so sneaky, like there are these hidden costs or drags that i didn't fully grasp when i signed the papers. is there a specific term for that feeling of the interest working against you so heavily at the start?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, the feeling you are describing relates to the concept of \"front-loading interest\" inherent in standard amortization schedules. Because the principal is highest at the beginning, the interest charge is also at its maximum before it gradually tapers off over time. While this isn't officially labeled with a single negative marketing term, it is often referred to by financial advisors as a \"front-loaded cost\" or \"premium interest\" that slightly diminishes any potential compound interest savings early on.",
